@DoodleBop, a lot of today's nastys come in java form, which requires no authorization, the script can deploy secretly. However, after unpacking the payload and compiling the application, most AVs will eventually pick up the objects, alot of the time not by heuristics though, but by the old fashioned definition comparison, aka manual scan. Stopping the actual java script, is a different thing altogether.

Ima MCP & CCNA, and this is based on machines with malwarebytes anti-malware aswell as eset nod32, both with real time enabled.

